04543nam a22006375i 9781477308066DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773080667 a10.7560/3025142doi  a(DE-B1597)587871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1993.5.M6bB47 2015 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309722231 aBerg, Charles Ramírez, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Classical Mexican Cinema :bThe Poetics of the Exceptional Golden Age Films /cCharles Ramírez Berg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction: Retheorizing Mexican Film History -- tChapter 2. Every Picture Tells a Story: José Guadalupe Posada’s Protocinematic Graphic Art -- tChapter 3. Enrique Rosas’s El automóvil gris (1919) and the Dawning of Modern Mexican Cinema -- tChapter 4. The Adoption of the Hollywood Style and the Transition to Sound -- tChapter 5. Mexican Cinema Comes of Age: Fernando de Fuentes in the 1930s -- tChapter 6. The Cinematic Invention of Mexico: The Poetics and Politics of the Fernández Unit Style -- tChapter 7. Luis Buñuel in Mexico -- tChapter 8. Three Classical Mexican Cinema Genre Films -- tChapter 9. Conclusion: What Happened to the Classical Mexican Cinema? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the mid-1930s to the late 1950s, Mexican cinema became the most successful Latin American cinema and the leading Spanish-language film industry in the world. Many Cine de Oro (Golden Age cinema) films adhered to the dominant Hollywood model, but a small yet formidable filmmaking faction rejected Hollywood’s paradigm outright. Directors Fernando de Fuentes, Emilio Fernández, Luis Buñuel, Juan Bustillo Oro, Adolfo Best Maugard, and Julio Bracho sought to create a unique national cinema that, through the stories it told and the ways it told them, was wholly Mexican. The Classical Mexican Cinema traces the emergence and evolution of this Mexican cinematic aesthetic, a distinctive film form designed to express lo mexicano. Charles Ramírez Berg begins by locating the classical style’s pre-cinematic roots in the work of popular Mexican artist José Guadalupe Posada at the turn of the twentieth century. He also looks at the dawning of Mexican classicism in the poetics of Enrique Rosas’ El Automóvil Gris, the crowning achievement of Mexico’s silent filmmaking era and the film that set the stage for the Golden Age films. Berg then analyzes mature examples of classical Mexican filmmaking by the predominant Golden Age auteurs of three successive decades. Drawing on neoformalism and neoauteurism within a cultural studies framework, he brilliantly reveals how the poetics of Classical Mexican Cinema deviated from the formal norms of the Golden Age to express a uniquely Mexican sensibility thematically, stylistically, and ideologically.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMotion picture industryzMexicoxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszMexicoxHistory. 0aMotion pictures, MexicanxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30251440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308066423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308066/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK